[src:candy-cummings/1872-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1872 throughout the world.
[src:candy-cummings/1873-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1873 throughout the world.
[src:candy-cummings/1874-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1874 throughout the world.
[src:candy-cummings/1875-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1875 throughout the world.
[src:candy-cummings/1876-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1876 throughout the world.
[src:candy-cummings/1876-in-baseball] After a tumultuous five-year existence, the National Association of Professional Base Ball Players (NA) folded following the 1875 season.
[src:candy-cummings/1876-in-baseball] One of the new rules put into place by the new league was that all teams had to be located in cities that had a population of 75,000 or more.
[src:candy-cummings/1876-in-baseball] The initial NL season began with eight teams, and they were asked to play seventy games between April 22 and October 21.
[src:candy-cummings/1876-in-baseball] The NL is often considered to be the first "major league", although it has been argued that the NA can make that claim.
[src:candy-cummings/1877-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1877 throughout the world.
[src:candy-cummings/1939-baseball-hall-of-fame-balloting] The 1939 elections to select inductees to the Baseball Hall of Fame were the last ones conducted prior to the Hall's opening that year.
[src:candy-cummings/1939-baseball-hall-of-fame-balloting] Needing just one addition to complete the initial goal of 10 inductees from the 20th century, members of the Baseball Writers' Association of America (BBWAA) were once again given authority to select any players active in the 20th century, excepting active players.
[src:candy-cummings/1939-baseball-hall-of-fame-balloting] In the BBWAA election, voters were instructed to cast votes for 10 candidates; any candidate receiving votes on at least 75% of the ballots would be honored with induction to the Hall upon its opening in Cooperstown, New York, on June 12 of that year.
[src:candy-cummings/1939-baseball-hall-of-fame-balloting] After the Hall's opening, a special election was also held in December.
[src:candy-cummings/1939-baseball-hall-of-fame-balloting] A total of 274 ballots were cast, with 2,710 individual votes for 108 specific candidates, an average of 9.89 per ballot; 206 votes were required for election.
[src:candy-cummings/1939-baseball-hall-of-fame-balloting] Although three stars of the 1920s did very well, the balloting was otherwise dominated by players of the 1900s and 1910s, who many voters felt should be given priority.
[src:candy-cummings/1939-baseball-hall-of-fame-balloting] Players who had been retired over 20 years received 60% of the votes, and accounted for 14 of the top 20 in the balloting.
[src:candy-cummings/1939-baseball-hall-of-fame-balloting] Due to frustration over the fact that no 19th century players had yet been selected, a number of players from that era whose careers extended into the 20th century only briefly (or not at all) even received some votes, as did some managers.
[src:candy-cummings/1939-baseball-hall-of-fame-balloting] The results were announced in January 1939.
[src:candy-cummings/1939-baseball-hall-of-fame-balloting] As the opening of the Hall approached, criticism mounted that no 19th century figures who were known primarily as players had yet been selected, when basic plans nearly four years earlier had promised five as an ideal initial number.
[src:candy-cummings/1939-baseball-hall-of-fame-balloting] In addition, the six-member Centennial Commission which had selected honorees in the previous two years never had an opportunity to meet.
[src:candy-cummings/1939-baseball-hall-of-fame-balloting] They chose six inductees, all of whom were deceased; of the 13 committee selections between 1937 and 1939, only Connie Mack was still living at the time of the Hall's opening (his Athletics played in the inaugural Hall of Fame game).
[src:candy-cummings/1939-baseball-hall-of-fame-balloting] At the major league winter meetings in Cincinnati in December 1939, the BBWAA held a special election to act on Lou Gehrig, who had announced his retirement that summer after being diagnosed with amyotrophic lateral sclerosis.
[src:candy-cummings/1939-baseball-hall-of-fame-balloting] The writers elected Gehrig to the Hall of Fame (the results of that election are unknown) and also determined to postpone the next regular election until 1942, as the initial quota of 10 inductees from the 20th century had been met.
[src:candy-cummings/candy-cummings] Cummings was born in Ware, Massachusetts, on October 18, 1848.
[src:candy-cummings/candy-cummings] Four years later, his family moved to Brooklyn, New York.
[src:candy-cummings/candy-cummings] He attended Falley Seminary in Fulton, New York, from 1864 to 1866, and played for Falley's baseball team.
[src:candy-cummings/candy-cummings] He pitched his team to the county championship.
[src:candy-cummings/candy-cummings] After graduating from Falley, Cummings joined the Star Base Ball Club, one of Brooklyn's best clubs, pitching for its junior squad.
[src:candy-cummings/candy-cummings] (Prior to the formal introduction of professional baseball in 1871, all baseball clubs were amateur.) Showing great promise, he was lured to another top Brooklyn club, Excelsior.
[src:candy-cummings/candy-cummings] At the age of 17, Cummings made his debut in the National Association of Base Ball Players with the Excelsior senior team.
[src:candy-cummings/candy-cummings] His first game with the Excelsior seniors was on August 14, 1866, against the New York Mutuals.
[src:candy-cummings/candy-cummings] For his performance, he received prophetic praise from the *Brooklyn Eagle*: "[H]e has only to keep on in the way he has begun, and he will one day (not far distant) be ranked among the best pitchers of the country." Two weeks later, he led his team to a 24–12 win against the Newark Eurekas.
[src:candy-cummings/candy-cummings] After the latter game, baseball writer Henry Chadwick commented on the skills of the young Cummings and his promising future with the Excelsior club.
[src:candy-cummings/candy-cummings] Cummings played for the Excelsiors next season, and continued as the main pitcher for the Stars of Brooklyn from 1868 to 1871.
[src:candy-cummings/candy-cummings] His pitching skills led to his being called "Candy", a popular 19th-century nickname for a man who was the best at his craft.
[src:candy-cummings/candy-cummings] Cummings, who stood 5'9" and weighed 120 pounds, compiled a 145–94 career record and 2.42 earned run average while playing for five different professional teams from 1872 to 1877.
[src:candy-cummings/candy-cummings] Between 1872 and 1875, he pitched in the National Association of Professional Base Ball Players (NA) with the New York Mutuals, Baltimore Canaries, Philadelphia White Stockings and Hartford Dark Blues.
[src:candy-cummings/candy-cummings] Cummings won 63.3% of his games over his four NA seasons.
[src:candy-cummings/candy-cummings] In 1876, when the National League (NL) was founded, he was still with the Hartford club, which was one of the league's founders, and compiled a 16–8 pitching record.
[src:candy-cummings/candy-cummings] In December 1876, he signed with a semi-professional club in Lynn, Massachusetts, the Live Oaks, to pitch and manage the club in 1877.
[src:candy-cummings/candy-cummings] He represented the Live Oaks at a convention that founded the International Association for Professional Base Ball Players, and was elected the association's first president.
[src:candy-cummings/candy-cummings] In the middle of the 1877, he left the Live Oaks and returned to the NA, pitching for the Cincinnati Reds, where he appeared in only 19 games and posted a 5–14 win-loss record.
[src:candy-cummings/candy-cummings] Among other records, Cummings was the first player to pitch two complete games in one day: September 9, 1876, when he beat the Cincinnati Red Stockings twice, 14–4 and 8–4.
[src:candy-cummings/candy-cummings] Cummings is often credited with being the inventor of the curveball.
[src:candy-cummings/candy-cummings] In his biography of Cummings, published in 2022, Stephen Katz provides proof.
[src:candy-cummings/candy-cummings] According to Cummings, he discovered the idea of the curveball while studying the movement sea shells made when thrown.
[src:candy-cummings/candy-cummings] After noticing this movement, he began trying to make a baseball move the same way, and thus created the new pitch.
[src:candy-cummings/candy-cummings] Cummings pitched the curveball underhand, as required by the rules of the National Association of Base Ball Players, but with a twist and snap of the wrist, which was illegal under the rules of the National Association of Base Ball Players.
[src:candy-cummings/candy-cummings] Those rules required the pitcher to deliver pitches with a straight arm, swinging perpendicularly by his side.
[src:candy-cummings/candy-cummings] But the rules were progressively relaxed so as to permit the arm and wrist motion that were necessary for pitching the curveball.
[src:candy-cummings/candy-cummings] Cummings first used the curveball in competition while pitching for Brooklyn's Excelsior club, in a game on October 7, 1867, against the Harvard College team.
[src:candy-cummings/candy-cummings] He would later recall from that game: "A surge of joy flooded over me that I shall never forget.
[src:candy-cummings/candy-cummings] I felt like shouting out that I had made a ball curve. ...
[src:candy-cummings/candy-cummings] But I said not a word and saw many a batter at that game throw down his stick in disgust." Cummings' introduction of the curveball radically changed pitching, and fundamentally transformed the game of baseball.
[src:candy-cummings/candy-cummings] Several other pitchers claimed to have invented the curveball.
[src:candy-cummings/candy-cummings] Goldsmith maintained that he gave a demonstration of the pitch on August 16, 1870, at the Capitoline Grounds in Brooklyn, New York, and that renown sportswriter Henry Chadwick had covered it in the *Brooklyn Eagle* on August 17, 1870.
[src:candy-cummings/candy-cummings] However, Stephen Katz, in his biography of Cummings, shows that Goldsmith's claim was not credible, and that Goldsmith's reference to an article by Chadwick in the *Brooklyn Eagle* was likely fabricated.
[src:candy-cummings/candy-cummings] According to a 2002 article by ESPN's Steve Wulf, Cummings was "fairly well-connected" in baseball, as evidenced by his position with the International Association.
[src:candy-cummings/candy-cummings] Baseball leaders Chadwick, Harry Wright and Albert Spalding, among others, credited Cummings as the inventor of the curveball.
[src:candy-cummings/candy-cummings] In 1873, Cummings invented a railway coupling device, improving on the coupling device then in use, which was dangerous.
[src:candy-cummings/candy-cummings] He refined his design in 1876, and patented it in 1877.
[src:candy-cummings/candy-cummings] Cummings received a small royalty for his invention throughout his life.
[src:candy-cummings/candy-cummings] After organized baseball, Cummings moved to Athol, Massachusetts, where he owned and operated a paint and wallpaper shop.
[src:candy-cummings/candy-cummings] Cummings died in Toledo, Ohio, on May 17, 1924.
[src:candy-cummings/candy-cummings] He is buried at Aspen Grove Cemetery in Ware, Massachusetts.
[src:candy-cummings/candy-cummings] Cummings was posthumously inducted into the Baseball Hall of Fame in 1939.
